[30;1m20 | [0m[35mimperatively within the scope of that function.[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35mHowever, if you'd prefer, you can use "deferred" values as SchemaNode[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mkeyword arguments to a schema defined at module scope, and[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35msubsequently use "schema binding" to resolve them later.  This can[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35mmake your schema seem "more declarative": it allows you to group all[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mthe code that will be run when your schema is used together at module[0m

[30;1m181 | [0m[35mTo perform binding, the ``bind`` method of a schema node must be[0m

[30;1m184 | [0m[35mresolved.  In the above example:[0m

  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

[30;1m173 | [0m[35m          )[0m
[30;1m174 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m175 | [0m[35mWe use ``colander.deferred`` in its preferred manner here: as a[0m
[30;1m176 | [0m[35mdecorator to a function that takes two arguments.  For a schema node[0m
[30;1m177 | [0m[35mvalue to be considered deferred, it must be an instance of[0m
[30;1m178 | [0m[35m``colander.deferred`` and using that class as a decorator is the[0m
[30;1m179 | [0m[35measiest way to ensure that this happens.[0m
[30;1m180 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m154 | [0m[35m   which are passed during schema node construction by someone constructing a[0m
[30;1m155 | [0m[35m   schema for a particular purpose are not used internally by Colander; they[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35m   are instead only meaningful to higher-level systems which consume Colander[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35m   schemas.  Arbitrary keyword arguments are allowed to a schema node[0m
